ll execute      completely before exiting. The loop index I (q.v.) will be left unchanged.                                                      Example:                                                        : FOO 10 0 DO I 5 = IF LEAVE THEN I . LOOP ;  \ print 1 2 3 4 5                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           LINK ( -- )                                             -       "link"                                                          Set CURRENT @ to LAST, thereby linking the most recently        created word into the CURRENT (q.v.) vocabulary.                Example: CREATE FOO LINK  \ link FOO into the dictionary                                                                        LIST ( u -- )                                           F-79    "list"                                                          List the disk block with the number U. 64 characters will       be listed per line and each line will be preceded by a line     number. U will be stored in SCR (q.v.).                                                                                                                                                                                                                         ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           LITERAL ( w -- )      IMMEDIATE COMPILE-ONLY            F-79    "literal"                                                       Usage: [ computation ] LITERAL -- Compile W as a literal so     that the value W will be pushed to the stack when executing     the word currently being compiled. Used to compile values       that are computed at compile time.                              Example: : FOO [ 3 4 + ] LITERAL ;  \ FOO will return 7                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           LOAD ( u -- )                                           F-79    "load"                                                          Load disk block U via BLOCK (q.v.), save the state of the       current input buffer, set the loaded input buffer up for        interpretation, and call INTERPRET (q.v.). When INTERPRET       returns, restore the state of the input buffer. The state of    an input buffer consists of the variables BLK, >IN, and #TIB.   A disk block U is set up for interpretation by setting BLK      to U, >IN to 0, and #TIB to B/BUF (q.v.).                       Example: 1 LOAD  \ load first disk block                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           LOOKUP ( a1 a2 -- a f )                                 -       "look-up"                                                       Attempt to find a dictionary entry in the vocabulary at A2 that matches the packed string at A1. When such an entry is found,   return the NFA of the entry and true. When no such entry is     found, return A1 and false.                                     : FOO $" DUP" CONTEXT @ @ LOOKUP ;  \ look up DUP in CONTEXT                                                                    LOOP ( -- )           IMMEDIATE COMPILE-ONLY            F-79    :loop"                                                          Usage: DO ... LOOP -- LOOP is like +LOOP with an increment of 1.Example: : FOO 10 0 DO I . LOOP ;  \ counts from 0 to 9.                                                                                                                                        ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           LSHIFT ( w1 w2 -- w )  Code                             -       "l-shift" "left-shift"                                          Shift the bits of the machine word W1 to the left by W2 bit     positions, filling vacant bits with 0. Return the shifted       machine word.                                                   Example: BINARY 1111 2 LSHIFT  \ gives 111100                                                                                   M* ( n1 n2 -- d )                                       FIG     "m-star"                                                        Multiply N1 by N2 and return their product as a double word.    Example: -32768 2 M*  \ gives 0 -1                                                                                                                                                                                                                              ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           M/MOD ( d n -- nm nq )                                  -       "m-slash-mod"                                                   Divide the double word D by N and leave the resulting floored   quotient (NQ) and division remainder (NM) on the stack. This    is almost FIG FORTH's M/MOD, but this one is signed.            Example: 1 1 16 M/MOD  \ gives 1 4096                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           MARK ( -- a )         COMPILE-ONLY                      -       "mark"                                                          Compile a placeholder machine word (0) and mark its address     in the dictionary for later backpatching (see RESOLVE). Return  the address of the placeholder.                                 Example:                                                        : IF COMPILE (0BRANCH) MARK ; IMMEDIATE COMPILE-ONLY            \ actual definition of IF                                                                                                       MAX ( n n -- n )                                        F-79    "max"                                                           Return the greater one of two numbers on the stack.             Example: 5 7 MAX  \ gives 7                                                                                                     ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           MIN ( n n -- n )                                        F-79    "min"                                                           Return the smaller one of two numbers on the stack.             Example: 5 7 MIN  \ gives 5                                                                                                     MOD ( n1 n2 -- n )                                      F-79    "mod"                                                           Return the remainder (modulo) of the division N1/N2.            Example: 255 16 MOD  \ gives 15                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           MOVE ( a1 a2 n -- )                                     F-79    "move"                                                          Move N machine words from A1 to A2. Start moving at lower       addresses (like CMOVE). When N<1, do nothing.                   Example:                                                        10 ARRAY A  10 ARRAY B  A B 10 CELLS MOVE                       \ move the elements of array A to array B                                                                                       NEGATE ( n -- n )                                       F-79    "negate"                                                        Return the negative value of N.                                 Example: 10 NEGATE  \ gives -10                                                                                                                                                                 ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           NIP ( w1 w2 -- w2 )                                     EFORTH  "nip"                                                           Remove the second value on the stack, while leaving the top     value in place.                                                 Example: 1 2 3 NIP  \ gives 1 3                                                                                                 NOT ( w -- f )                                          F-79    "not"                                                           Return truth, if W is false and otherwise return false. This    word is the same as 0=, but its intention is logical negation   rather than comparison with 0.                                  Example: 1 2 = NOT  \ gives -1                                                                                                                                                                  ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           NUMBER ( a -- n )                                       FIG     NUMBER ( a -- n | d )                            DOUBLE SF      "number"                                                        Convert the string at A to a number and return its value. If    the string does not represent a valid number with respect to    the current base, report an error. When the double word set     is loaded and a comma is found in the string, a double size     value will be returned. See CONVERT.                            Example: : FOO $" 123 " NUMBER ;  \ gives  123                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           OR ( w1 w2 -- w )     Code                              F-79    "or"                                                            Return the bitwise logical OR of W1 and W2.                     Example: 7 11 OR  \ gives 15                                                                                                    OVER ( w1 w2 -- w1 w2 w1 )  Code                        F-79    "over"                                                          Push an extra copy of the second value on the stack (W1) to     the stack.                                                      Example: 1 2 3 OVER  \ gives 1 2 3 2                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           PAD ( -- a )                                            F-79    "pad"                                                           Return the address of a memory area that can be used for        temporary storage. 64 bytes can be used in either direction     from A. Pictured number conversion uses the memory A-1 toward   lower addresses. There may be significantly more than 64 bytes  of space between the PAD and the parameter stack. Use SP@ to    compute the actual amount of free space.                                                                                        PAGE ( -- )                                             SF      "page"                                                          Clear the console screen.                                                                                                                                                                       ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           PERFORMS ( -- )        COMPILE-ONLY                     -       "performs"                                                      Usage: : name CREATE ... PERFORMS word ... ;                    Fetch the subsequent word and store its parameter field address in the code field of the most recently created word (see CREATE and LAST). Used in defining words to alter the runtime action   of defined words. The word following PERFORMS must be a         primitive word. Otherwise use <BUILDS and DOES>.                Example:                                                        : CONSTANT CREATE , PERFORMS (CONST) LINK ;                     \ actual implementation of CONSTANT                                                                                                                                                                                                                             ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           PFA>CFA ( a -- a )                                      -       "p-f-a-to-c-f-a"                                                Given the parameter field address (PFA) of a word, move to its  code field address (CFA).                                       Example: ' QUIT PFA>CFA  \ CFA of QUIT                                                                                          PICK ( u -- w )                                         F-83    "pick"                                                          Fetch the U'th element from the stack an push an extra copy of  it. For example, 0 PICK is DUP, 1 PICK is OVER.                 Example: 1 2 3 2 PICK  \ gives 1 2 3 1                                                                                                                                                                                                                          ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           QUERY ( -- )                                            F-79    "query"                                                         Read up to 80 characters into the terminal input buffer (TIB)   using EXPECT and set up the TIB for interpretation by setting   BLK to 0, >IN to 0, and #TIB to the number of characters read.  Do not call INTERPRET, though.                                                                                                  QUIT ( -- )           DEFER (QUIT)                      F-79    "quit"                                                          Clear the return stack, direct input and output to the console, and enter the outer interpreter loop.                           Example:                                                        : FOO ." Hi!" QUIT ;  \ prints Hi! and exits without prompt                                                                     ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           R0 ( -- u )           CONSTANT                          FIG     "r-zero"                                                        The bottom of the return stack. Note that the stack may         grow upward or downward. On the 8086 it grows toward smaller    addresses.                                                                                                                      R> ( -- w ; w -- )    Code                              F-79    "r-from"                                                        Move one machine word from the return stack to the parameter    stack.                                                          Example: see -ROT                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           R@ ( -- w )           Code                              F-79    "r-fetch"                                                       Copy one machine word from the return stack to the parameter    stack.                                                          Example:                                                        : FOO R> R> R@ -ROT >R >R ;                                     \ fetch second word from return stack                                                                                           READ-BLOCK ( a u -- T | F )  Code                       -       "read-block"                                                    Read disk block U into a buffer at address A. Return true when  the read operation succeeded and otherwise return false.                                                                                                                                        ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           RECURSE ( -- )                                          EFORTH  "recurse"                                                       Compile the code field address (CFA) of the most recently       created word, i.e. the word that is currently being compiled.   The effect of RECURSE at run time is that the word will call    itself.                                                         Example:                                                        : FOO DUP 0= IF DROP 1 ELSE DUP 1- RECURSE * THEN ;             \ recursive factorial function                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           REPEAT ( -- )         IMMEDIATE COMPILE-ONLY            F-79    "repeat"                                                        Usage: BEGIN ... condition WHILE ... REPEAT -- Jump back to the BEGIN keyword of a BEGIN-WHILE-REPEAT loop. See WHILE.                                                                          RESET ( -- )                                            -       "reset"                                                         Finish cold-booting the FORTH system. Set the CURRENT and       CONTEXT dictionaries to FORTH, empty the disk buffers, set BASE to decimal, restore the default USER variable area, print a     welcome message, and abort execution, thereby transferring      control to the outer interpreter.                                                                                                                                                               ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           RESOLVE ( a -- )      COMPILE-ONLY                      -       "resolve"                                                       Replace the value of a previously marked (se MARK) machine word with the value of HERE. The combination MARK and RESOLVE is usedfor backpatching forward jumps. MARK marks the parameter of a   (BRANCH) or (0BRANCH) (q.v.) word and RESOLVE later patches thatparameter, thereby redirecting the branch to HERE.              Example:                                                        : THEN RESOLVE ; IMMEDIATE COMPILE-ONLY                         \ actual implementation of THEN                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           ROT ( w1 w2 w3 -- w2 w3 w1 )                            F-79    "rote"                                                          Rotate the third element on the stack to the top.               Example: 1 2 3 ROT  \ gives 2 3 1                                                                                               RP! ( a -- ; -- ??? )  Code                             FIG     "r-p-store"                                                     Set the return stack pointer to A. Note that the content of the return stack will be undefined after this operation.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           RP@ ( -- a )          Code                              FIG     "r-p-fetch"                                                     Push the value of the return stack pointer to the parameter     stack.                                                                                                                          RSHIFT ( w w -- w )   Code                              -       "r-shift" "right-shift"                                         Shift the bits of the machine word W1 to the right by W2 bit    positions, filling vacant bits with 0. Return the shifted       machine word. I.e., this is a logical shift, not an arithmetic  shift.                                                          Example: BINARY 111000 2 RSHIFT  \ gives 1110                                                                                                                                                   ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           RX? ( -- c T | F )    Code                              -       "r-x-question"                                                  Check if a character is available from the console device.      When a character is available, return the character and truth,  otherwise return false.                                                                                                         S0 ( -- a )           CONSTANT                          FIG     "s-zero"                                                        The bottom of the parameter stack.  Note that the stack may     grow upward or downward. On the 8086 it grows toward smaller    addresses.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      ( T3XFORTH Glossary )                                                                                                           SAVE-BUFFERS ( -- )                                     F-79    "save-buffers"                                                  Write all disk buffers that have been marked "updated" to       their corresponding disk blocks and clear their "updated"       flags. When a block cannot be written, report an error.         Example: see COPY                                                                                                               SCR ( -- a )          VARIABLE                          F-79    "s-c-r"                                                         The number of the disk block most recently listed by            LIST (q.v.).                                                    